# Backend Development Standards
# Extends base-standards.mdc ‚Äî do not duplicate rules defined there

---

## API Design

### REST Conventions
- Resource names: plural nouns (`/users`, `/projects`, not `/user`, `/getProjects`)
- HTTP verbs as intended: GET (read), POST (create), PUT (replace), PATCH (partial update), DELETE
- Status codes must be semantically correct:
  - `200 OK` ‚Äî successful read or update
  - `201 Created` ‚Äî successful creation (include `Location` header)
  - `204 No Content` ‚Äî successful delete
  - `400 Bad Request` ‚Äî client validation error (include field-level detail)
  - `401 Unauthorized` ‚Äî missing or invalid auth
  - `403 Forbidden` ‚Äî authenticated but not authorized
  - `404 Not Found` ‚Äî resource does not exist
  - `409 Conflict` ‚Äî state conflict (duplicate, concurrent modification)
  - `422 Unprocessable Entity` ‚Äî semantically invalid input
  - `500 Internal Server Error` ‚Äî never expose stack traces in production

### Error Response Format (all APIs)
```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "VALIDATION_ERROR",
    "message": "Human-readable description",
    "fields": [
      { "field": "email", "message": "Invalid email format" }
    ]
  }
}
```

### Versioning
- URL versioning: `/api/v1/`, `/api/v2/`
- Never break a published version without a deprecation period (minimum 2 sprints)

---

## Database

- Migrations must be reversible (up + down)
- No raw SQL strings with string interpolation ‚Äî always use parameterized queries
- Indexes required on: foreign keys, columns used in WHERE/ORDER BY in frequent queries
- Soft deletes preferred over hard deletes for user-facing data
- Timestamps: always store in UTC; always include `created_at`, `updated_at`

---

## Security

- Never log passwords, tokens, or PII
- Validate and sanitize all input at the boundary (before business logic)
- Rate limiting on all public endpoints
- Authentication via JWT or session ‚Äî never roll custom crypto
- Secrets from environment variables only ‚Äî never hardcoded, never in version control

---

## OpenAPI Specification

Every backend service must maintain an `ai-specs/specs/api-spec.yml`:

```yaml
openapi: "3.0.3"
info:
  title: "[Service Name] API"
  version: "1.0.0"
  description: "[What this service does]"
paths:
  /resource:
    get:
      summary: "List resources"
      # ... full spec
```

> Keep the spec in sync with implementation. The spec is the contract ‚Äî not the code.

---

## Python / FastAPI Specifics

```python
# Correct: typed endpoint with Pydantic models
from pydantic import BaseModel
from fastapi import FastAPI, HTTPException

class ItemCreate(BaseModel):
    name: str
    description: str | None = None

@app.post("/items", status_code=201, response_model=ItemResponse)
async def create_item(item: ItemCreate) -> ItemResponse:
    ...
```

- One router per domain ‚Äî no mega-routers
- Dependency injection for DB sessions and auth (`Depends()`)
- Background tasks via `BackgroundTasks` or Celery ‚Äî not threads

---

## Rust / Axum Specifics

- One module per domain (`auth`, `items`, `users`)
- Handler functions must not contain business logic ‚Äî delegate to service layer
- Use `thiserror` for library errors, `anyhow` for application errors
- All DB queries in repository layer ‚Äî handlers never touch the DB directly
